WEBVTT

00:05.605 --> 00:11.109
<i> (Narrator) Previously, on "The
Making of the Mob: New York"...</i>

00:11.111 --> 00:12.677
<i> At the turn of the</i>
<i> century,</i>

00:12.679 --> 00:14.311
<i> hundreds of thousands</i>
<i> of immigrants</i>

00:14.313 --> 00:17.614
<i> pour into New York City.</i>

00:17.616 --> 00:20.316
<i> And as ruthless gangs</i>
<i> carve out their turf,</i>

00:20.318 --> 00:23.285
<i> a new class of</i>
<i> mobster emerges.</i>

00:23.287 --> 00:25.253
<i> (Gunshot firing)</i>

00:25.255 --> 00:27.688
<i> Charles Luciano,</i>
<i> Meyer Lansky,</i>

00:27.690 --> 00:32.092
<i> Bugsy Siegel, Frank Costello,</i>
<i> and Vito Genovese</i>

00:32.094 --> 00:35.028
<i> climb their up the ranks</i>
<i> of the New York underworld,</i>

00:35.030 --> 00:37.163
<i> working under</i>
<i> ruthless mob boss,</i>

00:37.165 --> 00:39.098
<i> Joe Masseria.</i>

00:39.100 --> 00:42.334
<i> (Gunshot firing)</i>

00:42.336 --> 00:45.737
The street level group of
thugs who shook people down

00:45.739 --> 00:48.773
<i> organized into</i>
<i> a large number of thugs</i>

00:48.775 --> 00:50.174
<i> who were shaking</i>
<i> people down,</i>

00:50.176 --> 00:53.710
taking bets,
even sellin' drugs.

00:53.712 --> 00:59.348
<i> (Narrator) After Masseria's heroin
racket lands Luciano in prison,</i>

00:59.350 --> 01:02.184
<i> he joins forces with</i>
<i> Jewish criminal mastermind,</i>

01:02.186 --> 01:04.119
<i> Arnold Rothstein.</i>

01:04.121 --> 01:07.422
There's safety in no one
knowing who you are.

01:07.424 --> 01:10.358
<i> (Narrator) And decides
it's time for a change.</i>

01:10.360 --> 01:12.326
<i> (Rapid gunfire)</i>

01:16.264 --> 01:18.298
<i> But, to make it</i>
<i> to the top,</i>

01:18.300 --> 01:21.234
<i> Luciano and his crew will</i>
<i> have to make a bold move...</i>

01:21.236 --> 01:24.237
If I don't kill him,
we're all dead.

01:24.239 --> 01:27.206
<i> (Narrator) ... and take out the
one man standing in their way,</i>

01:27.208 --> 01:29.675
<i> Joe Masseria.</i>

01:29.677 --> 01:33.144
You got some big balls
comin' over here like this.

01:34.779 --> 01:39.282
<i> (Collective shouting)</i>

01:39.284 --> 01:44.253
You do this...
There's no goin' back.

01:44.255 --> 01:47.155
I know.

01:50.092 --> 01:53.394
<i> ♪ This ain't no time ♪</i>

01:53.396 --> 01:57.097
<i> ♪ to feel sorry for</i>
<i> myself♪</i>

01:57.099 --> 02:00.100
<i> ♪ I can't help it ♪</i>

02:00.102 --> 02:02.769
<i> ♪ cause there's nobody else</i>
<i> ♪</i>

02:03.871 --> 02:09.341
<i> ♪ I'll walk these streets
with your name on my tongue ♪</i>

02:10.843 --> 02:16.213
<i> ♪ but I dare not speak</i>
<i> only there it belongs ♪</i>

02:18.249 --> 02:21.584
<i> ♪ 'cause there's got</i>
<i> to be a better way ♪</i>

02:23.720 --> 02:26.288
<i> ♪ get away ♪</i>

02:37.533 --> 02:39.767
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> In less than two decades,</i>

02:39.769 --> 02:42.469
<i> 30-year-old Charles Luciano</i>
<i> and his gang</i>

02:42.471 --> 02:45.438
<i> have gone from</i>
<i> poor immigrants</i>

02:45.440 --> 02:48.174
<i> to successful</i>
<i> New York criminals,</i>

02:48.176 --> 02:51.377
<i> poised to eliminate the most
powerful gangster in New York,</i>

02:51.379 --> 02:54.213
<i> Joe Masseria.</i>

02:54.215 --> 02:56.515
<i> Thanks to the guidance</i>
<i> of his trusted advisor,</i>

02:56.517 --> 03:02.854
<i> notorious Jewish gangster,</i>
<i> Arnold Rothstein.</i>

03:02.856 --> 03:05.723
<i> (Meyer Lansky ii) Arnold Rothstein
was a mentor to Lucky Luciano.</i>

03:05.725 --> 03:07.424
<i> He was under his wing.</i>

03:07.426 --> 03:10.527
They showed 'em how to--
how to run this business.

03:10.529 --> 03:12.262
<i> (Indistinct chatter)</i>

03:12.264 --> 03:13.930
<i> (Meyer Lansky ii)</i>
<i> There was an alliance,</i>

03:13.932 --> 03:16.465
<i> and that stuck in his</i>
<i> heart.</i>

03:16.467 --> 03:18.400
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> To Luciano,</i>

03:18.402 --> 03:20.802
<i> Rothstein</i>
<i> is a father figure,</i>

03:20.804 --> 03:23.437
<i> and everything</i>
<i> he aspires to be.</i>

03:23.439 --> 03:24.905
Who does he report to?

03:24.907 --> 03:27.207
He reports to the
district attorney.

03:27.209 --> 03:28.908
<i> (Narrator) Rothstein is the
epitome of sophistication</i>

03:28.910 --> 03:31.510
<i> and self-control...</i>

03:33.913 --> 03:36.781
<i> ...but every man</i>
<i> has a weakness.</i>

03:36.783 --> 03:40.651
<i> And for Rothstein,</i>
<i> it's high stakes gambling.</i>

03:43.221 --> 03:47.324
Without a doubt, the mob will eat away
at your personality and at your soul.

03:47.326 --> 03:49.893
<i> You have this weight that
you're carrying around with you.</i>

03:49.895 --> 03:52.462
<i> Now, some guys are able</i>
<i> to shed it with alcohol.</i>

03:52.464 --> 03:54.497
They shed it with sex.
They shed it with drugs.

03:54.499 --> 03:57.600
But, eventually,
it's gonna wear on you.

03:57.602 --> 03:59.201
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> For most of his life,</i>

03:59.203 --> 04:02.871
<i> Rothstein has been</i>
<i> a compulsive gambler,</i>

04:02.873 --> 04:04.472
<i> from betting on horses,</i>

04:04.474 --> 04:05.940
<i> to being the man</i>
<i> believed to have fixed</i>

04:05.942 --> 04:09.944
<i> the 1919 world series.</i>

04:09.946 --> 04:14.214
<i> But Rothstein's addiction has</i>
<i> finally caught up with him.</i>

04:14.216 --> 04:21.286
♪♪

04:24.523 --> 04:27.491
How bad is it, Arnold?
What happened?

04:27.493 --> 04:29.993
It's fine.
don't--

04:29.995 --> 04:33.429
it's fine.

04:33.431 --> 04:35.531
<i> In September 1928,</i>

04:35.533 --> 04:40.935
Arnold Rothstein's luck
is starting to run bad.

04:40.937 --> 04:43.437
<i> He's been losing</i>
<i> at the track.</i>

04:43.439 --> 04:45.939
<i> He's been losing at</i>
<i> cards.</i>

04:45.941 --> 04:49.375
<i> His marriage is also</i>
<i> deteriorating badly.</i>

04:49.377 --> 04:52.244
When does he quit?
When does he have enough money?

04:57.315 --> 04:59.249
I'll raise you 500.

05:02.953 --> 05:05.587
He's invited
to a big game.

05:05.589 --> 05:07.956
<i> The big out of town</i>
<i> guys are there.</i>

05:13.462 --> 05:16.297
<i> Rothstein goes on,</i>
<i> and on, and on,</i>

05:16.299 --> 05:19.400
<i> for three days,</i>
<i> losing steadily.</i>

05:19.402 --> 05:26.473
♪♪

05:33.513 --> 05:35.680
<i> (Man)</i>
<i> Jacks over nines.</i>

05:39.918 --> 05:42.486
<i> He makes a couple of bets</i>
<i> at the end and he says,</i>

05:42.488 --> 05:47.991
"Okay, it's fixed,
and I'm not paying."

05:47.993 --> 05:55.064
♪♪

06:16.085 --> 06:20.488
<i> (Telephone ringing)</i>

06:20.490 --> 06:22.556
Yeah.

06:25.326 --> 06:27.593
Okay.

06:32.365 --> 06:39.437
♪♪

06:41.406 --> 06:43.573
What?

06:48.678 --> 06:50.445
Rothstein's dead.

06:50.447 --> 06:57.518
♪♪

07:03.991 --> 07:07.126
<i> (Narrator) News of the first
assassination of a New York kingpin</i>

07:07.128 --> 07:11.096
<i> makes headlines</i>
<i> across the country.</i>

07:11.098 --> 07:13.698
<i> On November 4th, 1928,</i>

07:13.700 --> 07:18.469
<i> Arnold Rothstein was</i>
<i> gunned down in the streets.</i>

07:19.637 --> 07:22.438
<i> And dozens of big name
gangsters arrive in New York</i>

07:22.440 --> 07:27.075
<i> to attend Rothstein's</i>
<i> orthodox Jewish funeral.</i>

07:27.077 --> 07:29.410
<i> (Selwyn Raab) Arnold Rothstein
taught other people.</i>

07:29.412 --> 07:32.646
He was sort of an equal
opportunity, uh, mentor thief.

07:32.648 --> 07:34.080
<i> He didn't mind</i>
<i> helping Italian,</i>

07:34.082 --> 07:36.582
<i> or Irish, or</i>
<i> Jewish gangsters.</i>

07:36.584 --> 07:39.017
So, he had this cloud of
appreciation around him

07:39.019 --> 07:41.019
that he was such
an important guy.

07:41.021 --> 07:43.688
<i> (Birds chirping)</i>

07:44.523 --> 07:50.728
<i> (Narrator)</i> <i> For Luciano, the murder of
Arnold Rothstein is a crushing blow.</i>

07:50.730 --> 07:54.031
<i> With his trusted</i>
<i> advisor gone...</i>

07:55.433 --> 08:01.036
<i> He decides to put his plans to
take out Joe Masseria on hold.</i>

08:01.038 --> 08:04.606
<i> But while Luciano</i>
<i> questions his next move,</i>

08:04.608 --> 08:09.444
<i> an even bigger</i>
<i> problem is brewing.</i>

08:09.446 --> 08:12.146
<i> The federal government begins
to crack down on gang activity</i>

08:12.148 --> 08:13.780
<i> across the country,</i>

08:13.782 --> 08:15.815
<i> and for the first</i>
<i> time in years,</i>

08:15.817 --> 08:19.752
<i> New York City's mobsters</i>
<i> are under fire.</i>

08:19.754 --> 08:21.787
<i> In the spring of 1929,</i>

08:21.789 --> 08:24.523
<i> special government task</i>
<i> forces raid speakeasies</i>

08:24.525 --> 08:28.059
<i> and mob headquarters</i>
<i> throughout New York.</i>

08:28.061 --> 08:31.629
<i> It's part of a sweeping effort
to take down mobsters...</i>

08:31.631 --> 08:35.432
<i> Triggered by the actions</i>
<i> of a notorious gangster</i>

08:35.434 --> 08:41.136
<i> over 800 miles away</i>
<i> named Al Capone.</i>

08:41.138 --> 08:43.538
<i> (Rich Cohen) Al Capone
is a Brooklyn gangster</i>

08:43.540 --> 08:45.606
<i> who fled to Chicago,</i>

08:45.608 --> 08:50.477
and Chicago was a much
rougher city than New York.

08:50.479 --> 08:53.179
<i> (Woman screams)</i>

08:53.181 --> 08:54.279
Huh?

08:54.281 --> 08:58.083
<i> (Rich Cohen) And he operated
very well in that environment...</i>

08:58.085 --> 09:01.719
But, he didn't have
the tempering influence

09:01.721 --> 09:04.822
<i> of a Meyer Lansky,</i>
<i> who could say to Luciano,</i>

09:04.824 --> 09:07.224
"this is stupid."

09:07.226 --> 09:09.492
<i> He would do things</i>
<i> very much out in the public.</i>

09:09.494 --> 09:13.562
<i> Very much in the face</i>
<i> of law enforcement.</i>

09:13.564 --> 09:16.698
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> But on February 14th, 1929,</i>

09:16.700 --> 09:18.633
<i> Capone goes too far,</i>

09:18.635 --> 09:21.702
<i> ordering the brutal execution</i>
<i> of rival Chicago gangsters.</i>

09:21.704 --> 09:25.138
<i> (Rapid gunfire)</i>

09:30.643 --> 09:33.211
<i> More than 150</i>
<i> shots are fired,</i>

09:33.213 --> 09:35.846
<i> in what becomes known as</i>
<i> one of the bloodiest days</i>

09:35.848 --> 09:38.215
<i> in mafia history,</i>

09:38.217 --> 09:41.518
<i> the Saint Valentine's</i>
<i> day massacre.</i>

09:41.520 --> 09:44.854
<i> (michael green) The Saint Valentine's
day massacre is so incredible,</i>

09:44.856 --> 09:46.856
<i> it gets attention.</i>

09:46.858 --> 09:49.124
There is more unhappiness
in the public

09:49.126 --> 09:52.560
that there is this
stuff going on.

09:52.562 --> 09:55.596
<i> The mob tried to fly</i>
<i> under the radar.</i>

09:55.598 --> 09:58.265
And when they got
people's attention,

09:58.267 --> 10:00.734
it could be very
bad for them.

10:09.210 --> 10:11.678
<i> (Narrator) With the feds
sweeping the country,</i>

10:11.680 --> 10:14.213
<i> New York mob boss,</i>
<i> Joe Masseria,</i>

10:14.215 --> 10:18.884
<i> has to act fast to take the
heat off of his operation.</i>

10:18.886 --> 10:21.819
<i> He knows he needs to get</i>
<i> Capone under control.</i>

10:25.658 --> 10:27.859
<i> (Joe Masseria) It's a
shame about your friend.</i>

10:27.861 --> 10:31.362
He picked a bad time
to get sloppy.

10:31.364 --> 10:33.831
<i> (Narrator) Knowing Al
Capone and Luciano ran</i>

10:33.833 --> 10:37.301
<i> in the same New York</i>
<i> gangs as teenagers,</i>

10:37.303 --> 10:40.270
<i> Masseria is convinced</i>
<i> that Luciano is the only one</i>

10:40.272 --> 10:44.874
<i> in his organization that can</i>
<i> get close enough to Capone.</i>

10:50.780 --> 10:52.947
<i> Luciano must now</i>
<i> do something</i>

10:52.949 --> 10:57.984
<i> that no one has been</i>
<i> able to do before...</i>

10:57.986 --> 11:01.053
<i> Reign in Al Capone.</i>

11:01.055 --> 11:07.325
♪♪

11:14.765 --> 11:17.399
<i> (Narrator) With the feds cracking
down on the mob's activities</i>

11:17.401 --> 11:20.935
<i> in the wake of the Saint
Valentine's day massacre,</i>

11:20.937 --> 11:23.037
<i> Joe Masseria orders</i>
<i> Charles Luciano</i>

11:23.039 --> 11:27.007
<i> to take care of the most violent
gangster in the country,</i>

11:27.009 --> 11:29.275
<i> Al Capone.</i>

11:34.714 --> 11:36.381
<i> In may of 1929,</i>

11:36.383 --> 11:39.050
<i> Luciano organizes a</i>
<i> top secret mob conference</i>

11:39.052 --> 11:42.386
<i> at the ritz-Carlton,</i>
<i> in Atlantic city...</i>

11:42.388 --> 11:44.955
<i> Owned by the mob boss</i>
<i> of New Jersey,</i>

11:44.957 --> 11:48.892
<i> Enoch "Nucky" Johnson.</i>

11:48.894 --> 11:51.327
<i> Up-and-coming Jewish, Irish,</i>
<i> and Italian gangsters</i>

11:51.329 --> 11:53.929
<i> from across the country</i>
<i> are invited,</i>

11:53.931 --> 11:57.065
<i> including Capone.</i>

11:57.067 --> 12:00.435
All right...
I wanna get this started.

12:00.437 --> 12:01.969
Take your seats.

12:01.971 --> 12:08.475
♪♪

12:08.477 --> 12:13.313
<i> (Enoch Johnson)</i> <i> The way I see it, Al's
made it impossible</i> <i> for us to do business.</i>

12:13.315 --> 12:17.116
Thanks to you,
my gambling is down.

12:17.118 --> 12:20.419
My rackets are down.

12:20.421 --> 12:23.922
Every one of my clubs
has been raided, twice!

12:26.926 --> 12:31.728
You're a popular guy.

12:31.730 --> 12:33.062
I think I speak
for all of us,

12:33.064 --> 12:38.066
when I say, uh,
you're not.

12:38.068 --> 12:42.136
<i> We all know what</i>
<i> needs to happen.</i>

12:42.138 --> 12:44.938
Al's gotta
give himself up.

12:44.940 --> 12:51.778
♪♪

12:51.780 --> 12:55.515
I'm not gonna be
a sacrificial lamb.

12:55.517 --> 12:57.483
'Cause Christ almighty
can come down,

12:57.485 --> 12:59.017
walk across the water,

12:59.019 --> 13:00.418
and ask me to
turn myself in,

13:00.420 --> 13:04.889
<i> and I'd still say "no."</i>

13:04.891 --> 13:07.858
Gentlemen, excuse us.
Let's go for a walk.

13:10.027 --> 13:12.895
<i> (Michael Green) Lucky Luciano
had a variety of ways</i>

13:12.897 --> 13:14.830
<i> of winning people over.</i>

13:14.832 --> 13:16.431
It might be fear.

13:16.433 --> 13:18.933
It-it might be good
business techniques.

13:18.935 --> 13:21.502
<i> It might be a willingness</i>
<i> to work with other people.</i>

13:21.504 --> 13:22.836
He's a threat.

13:22.838 --> 13:24.971
Uh, he has muscle
behind him,

13:24.973 --> 13:27.473
and he's willing to
put the muscle to work.

13:27.475 --> 13:30.943
<i> (Waves splashing)</i>

13:37.516 --> 13:40.918
The law, it's not
letting up on this one.

13:40.920 --> 13:45.055
I don't care.
You better care.

13:45.057 --> 13:47.891
It's about
the greater good.

13:47.893 --> 13:50.093
I gotta look out
for myself.

13:50.095 --> 13:52.061
And so do I.

13:54.030 --> 13:55.830
You know,
i could help you, Al,

13:55.832 --> 13:58.265
but if you don't listen to me,
i can't protect you.

14:01.402 --> 14:04.504
We got friends in the
d.A.'S office, in Philly.

14:04.506 --> 14:06.439
You plead to
a minor charge.

14:06.441 --> 14:07.940
I look after your
business in Chicago,

14:07.942 --> 14:11.043
and when you get out,
it'll be waiting for you.

14:21.520 --> 14:23.554
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> In a bold masterstroke,</i>

14:23.556 --> 14:27.457
<i> Luciano convinces Capone</i>
<i> to take the fall.</i>

14:27.459 --> 14:29.592
<i> And with the mob's</i>
<i> connections,</i>

14:29.594 --> 14:32.227
<i> Capone is sentenced to</i>
<i> just a year in prison.</i>

14:32.229 --> 14:37.565
♪♪

14:37.567 --> 14:40.034
<i> Following in Arnold</i>
<i> Rothstein's footsteps,</i>

14:40.036 --> 14:43.170
<i> Luciano has proven himself</i>
<i> a skillful leader</i>

14:43.172 --> 14:46.606
<i> and effective negotiator.</i>

14:46.608 --> 14:49.041
<i> Respect to a man</i>
<i> like Lucky</i>

14:49.043 --> 14:52.010
meant that everybody
listened to him.

14:52.012 --> 14:54.112
Almost like a
director in a play.

14:54.114 --> 14:56.414
They listened to him.
They trusted him.

14:56.416 --> 15:00.251
<i> He was in control.</i>

15:00.253 --> 15:02.553
<i> (Narrator) Luciano was
earned a new level of respect</i>

15:02.555 --> 15:05.556
<i> from gangsters</i>
<i> around the country,</i>

15:05.558 --> 15:07.157
<i> but his criminal</i>
<i> abilities</i>

15:07.159 --> 15:10.193
<i> are about to be put</i>
<i> to the ultimate test.</i>

15:15.465 --> 15:19.100
<i> On October 28th, 1929,</i>

15:19.102 --> 15:21.635
<i> the U.S. stock</i>
<i> market crashes,</i>

15:21.637 --> 15:26.506
<i> losing billions of dollars</i>
<i> in just one day.</i>

15:26.508 --> 15:28.140
<i> It's the worst</i>
<i> economic disaster</i>

15:28.142 --> 15:31.076
<i> the country</i>
<i> has ever seen.</i>

15:31.078 --> 15:33.178
<i> Nine thousand banks fail,</i>

15:33.180 --> 15:36.247
<i> and one in four Americans</i>
<i> are unemployed.</i>

15:40.151 --> 15:42.018
<i> But while most people</i>
<i> see the great depression</i>

15:42.020 --> 15:45.121
<i> as a time of</i>
<i> hopelessness,</i>

15:45.123 --> 15:50.025
<i> Luciano sees it as</i>
<i> a new opportunity.</i>

15:50.027 --> 15:52.227
<i> Together,</i>
<i> with Meyer Lansky,</i>

15:52.229 --> 15:54.629
<i> he develops</i>
<i> a new racket,</i>

15:54.631 --> 15:59.934
<i> designed to take advantage</i>
<i> of the economic depression.</i>

15:59.936 --> 16:02.536
<i> Using the millions they've
made from bootlegging,</i>

16:02.538 --> 16:04.237
<i> they begin providing</i>
<i> loans to businesses</i>

16:04.239 --> 16:06.973
<i> on the verge of</i>
<i> bankruptcy,</i>

16:06.975 --> 16:09.241
<i> at extremely high</i>
<i> interest rates.</i>

16:09.243 --> 16:11.243
<i> (michael green) Just as
prohibition was good for the mob,</i>

16:11.245 --> 16:14.112
<i> the depression was</i>
<i> good for the mob.</i>

16:14.114 --> 16:16.314
Banks are going under.
People need money.

16:16.316 --> 16:18.949
People need to get loans.

16:18.951 --> 16:21.217
<i> (Narrator) With Meyer Lansky
in charge of the finances,</i>

16:21.219 --> 16:23.953
<i> Luciano and his crew</i>
<i> are using their new racket</i>

16:23.955 --> 16:26.555
<i> to make a fortune.</i>

16:26.557 --> 16:29.124
You just couldn't go
to a bank and say,

16:29.126 --> 16:30.658
"could you loan me
some money?

16:30.660 --> 16:32.059
"Uh, my rent is due."

16:32.061 --> 16:33.593
<i> You couldn't say,</i>
<i> "loan me some money.</i>

16:33.595 --> 16:35.261
<i> "I gotta get my kid</i>
<i> through college,"</i>

16:35.263 --> 16:37.129
<i> because they weren't</i>
<i> gonna give you a loan.</i>

16:37.131 --> 16:40.565
So, you would go to people that
they called "loan sharks,"

16:40.567 --> 16:44.068
<i> and, look, credit cards</i>
<i> charge up to 18% interest,</i>

16:44.070 --> 16:46.570
<i> and the interest from</i>
<i> a loan shark is 20%.</i>

16:46.572 --> 16:48.271
<i> So, what's the difference</i>
<i> if you borrowed money</i>

16:48.273 --> 16:49.939
<i> from chase Manhattan</i>
<i> bank,</i>

16:49.941 --> 16:51.607
or borrowed money
from the street?

16:51.609 --> 16:58.680
♪♪

17:03.185 --> 17:05.653
Thought I might
find you here.

17:05.655 --> 17:07.721
Bugsy, it was just
a misunderstanding.

17:07.723 --> 17:10.123
<i> (Chuckles)</i>

17:12.126 --> 17:14.627
Misunderstanding?

17:14.629 --> 17:16.362
You know, that's okay,

17:16.364 --> 17:17.629
because people have
misunderstandings

17:17.631 --> 17:19.964
all the time.

17:19.966 --> 17:22.066
For instance,
i don't understand

17:22.068 --> 17:26.036
how you think that you
can borrow money from me...

17:26.038 --> 17:28.605
(Chuckles)
And not pay me back.

17:28.607 --> 17:31.074
<i> (Grunts)</i>

17:31.076 --> 17:32.508
That's a horrible
misunderstanding.

17:37.213 --> 17:39.547
Do you mind if
i finish this off?

17:39.549 --> 17:42.082
<i> (Grunts)</i>

17:48.688 --> 17:53.425
You'll remember, next time,
to pay me the money!

17:53.427 --> 17:55.293
<i> (Alexander Hortis) There were the cases
where they would break your knees,</i>

17:55.295 --> 17:56.394
<i> or they'd break your</i>
<i> legs.</i>

17:56.396 --> 17:58.662
And, as a result,
people learned,

17:58.664 --> 18:00.296
they paid off the mafia.

18:00.298 --> 18:03.365
They paid off the mafia
before you pay off a bank.

18:03.367 --> 18:06.334
And when they can't,
the mafia would say,

18:06.336 --> 18:09.670
"okay, well, then we're gonna
own 10% of your business."

18:14.375 --> 18:17.377
<i> (Narrator) While America's
in financial ruin,</i>

18:17.379 --> 18:20.413
<i> Luciano and his crew</i>
<i> are making a fortune.</i>

18:20.415 --> 18:24.049
<i> The mob owns a stake in</i>
<i> businesses across New York,</i>

18:24.051 --> 18:29.254
<i> and Luciano is earning</i>
<i> 20% interest, every week.</i>

18:29.256 --> 18:32.790
<i> Still forced to kick</i>
<i> money up to Joe Masseria,</i>

18:32.792 --> 18:36.026
<i> Luciano believes the time</i>
<i> is finally right</i>

18:36.028 --> 18:38.161
<i> to remove the only person</i>
<i> standing his way</i>

18:38.163 --> 18:41.097
<i> of getting to the top</i>
<i> of the New York underworld.</i>

18:43.100 --> 18:45.668
<i> But before Luciano</i>
<i> can make his move,</i>

18:45.670 --> 18:47.703
<i> a new rival</i>
<i> strikes first.</i>

18:47.705 --> 18:49.404
<i> (Rapid gunfire)</i>

18:49.406 --> 18:56.477
♪♪

19:16.363 --> 19:19.331
<i> (Narrator) A surprise attack leaves
one of Joe Masseria's warehouses</i>

19:19.333 --> 19:21.399
<i> in ruins.</i>

19:23.668 --> 19:26.736
<i> The man behind the assault</i>
<i> is determined to muscle in</i>

19:26.738 --> 19:31.340
<i> on Joe Masseria's</i>
<i> territory.</i>

19:31.342 --> 19:34.241
<i> He's a rival mob boss</i>
<i> from sicily...</i>

19:36.310 --> 19:39.812
<i> And he's just</i>
<i> started a war</i>

19:39.814 --> 19:44.283
<i> with the biggest kingpin</i>
<i> in New York, Joe Masseria.</i>

19:49.722 --> 19:52.356
<i> (Narrator) Joe "the boss" Masseria
has ruled the New York underworld</i>

19:52.358 --> 19:55.292
<i> for the past decade.</i>

19:55.294 --> 19:58.562
<i> But, in may of 1930,</i>

19:58.564 --> 20:00.597
<i> one of his warehouses</i>
<i> comes under attack.</i>

20:00.599 --> 20:02.532
<i> (Rapid gunfire)</i>

20:02.534 --> 20:09.605
♪♪

20:25.922 --> 20:27.856
<i> (Narrator) Masseria's
empire has been targeted</i>

20:27.858 --> 20:31.259
<i> by a ruthless, well-funded</i>
<i> sicilian mob boss</i>

20:31.261 --> 20:34.228
<i> named Salvatore</i>
<i> Maranzano.</i>

20:34.230 --> 20:39.266
<i> In the late 1920's, there was a rival
Italian</i> <i> gang headquartered in</i> <i> Brooklyn,</i>

20:39.268 --> 20:43.869
known as "the Castellammarese,"
and they came from sicily.

20:43.871 --> 20:45.370
<i> And their leader</i>
<i> was a man</i>

20:45.372 --> 20:48.973
<i> by the name of</i>
<i> Salvatore Maranzano.</i>

20:48.975 --> 20:50.541
<i> (Narrator) Maranzano has
been sent to New York</i>

20:50.543 --> 20:53.477
<i> by mafia bosses</i>
<i> in sicily.</i>

20:57.315 --> 20:58.581
<i> The mafia's power</i>
<i> is being crushed</i>

20:58.583 --> 21:03.318
<i> by the rise of a tyrannical</i>
<i> young dictator,</i>

21:03.320 --> 21:06.287
<i> Benito Mussolini.</i>

21:06.289 --> 21:07.888
<i> For the past century,</i>

21:07.890 --> 21:12.559
<i> the sicilian mafia</i>
<i> has dominated Italy.</i>

21:12.561 --> 21:16.963
Mussolini saw that one of his
big problems was the mafia.

21:16.965 --> 21:20.433
<i> That they wouldn't</i>
<i> bend to his will.</i>

21:20.435 --> 21:25.437
<i> So, he just rounded up what he
considered suspected mafiosos</i>

21:25.439 --> 21:27.539
<i> and simply imprisoned</i>
<i> 'em.</i>

21:27.541 --> 21:30.875
And it led to one
of the largest exoduses

21:30.877 --> 21:33.944
of future mafia in America.

21:33.946 --> 21:36.680
So, Mussolini was
unintentionally responsible

21:36.682 --> 21:40.316
<i> for helping to create</i>
<i> the American mafia.</i>

21:40.318 --> 21:47.389
♪♪

21:47.391 --> 21:49.424
<i> (Narrator) Salvatore
Maranzano has been sent</i>

21:49.426 --> 21:53.894
<i> to establish a foothold for
the sicilian mafia in America.</i>

21:53.896 --> 21:55.996
<i> And, in one strike,</i>

21:55.998 --> 22:00.000
<i> he's declared war on the</i>
<i> largest kingpin in New York,</i>

22:00.002 --> 22:02.569
<i> Joe Masseria.</i>

22:08.542 --> 22:11.544
This is a turf war.

22:11.546 --> 22:13.679
<i> We need to</i>
<i> come out on top.</i>

22:15.548 --> 22:18.983
I wanna know every
single move that he makes,

22:18.985 --> 22:22.052
<i> before he makes it.</i>

22:22.054 --> 22:24.687
<i> If you even suspect</i>
<i> anybody's with Maranzano,</i>

22:24.689 --> 22:29.324
and I mean anybody...

22:29.326 --> 22:32.026
Kill him.

22:32.028 --> 22:33.694
<i> (Vincent Pastore) There's a lotta
wise guys compare themselves</i>

22:33.696 --> 22:36.530
<i> to soldiers in an army.</i>

22:36.532 --> 22:40.634
<i> When the general says,</i> "you guys gotta
go hit that hill and kill the enemy,"

22:40.636 --> 22:43.570
it's the same as a don
in a family saying,

22:43.572 --> 22:46.940
"you guys gotta go take
these other guys out."

22:46.942 --> 22:49.008
<i> You're takin' orders.</i>

22:52.645 --> 22:59.717
♪♪

23:05.723 --> 23:08.691
<i> (Rapid gunfire)</i>

23:08.693 --> 23:11.360
<i> (Engine sputtering)</i>

23:15.131 --> 23:17.765
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> In may of 1930...</i>

23:21.069 --> 23:25.539
<i> An all-out war</i>
<i> breaks out...</i>

23:25.541 --> 23:28.108
<i> As Joe Masseria</i>
<i> and Salvatore Maranzano</i>

23:28.110 --> 23:31.544
<i> fight for control</i>
<i> of New York.</i>

23:38.117 --> 23:39.083
<i> (Woman screaming)</i>

23:39.085 --> 23:40.951
<i> (Gunshots firing)</i>

23:45.122 --> 23:47.022
<i> (Gunshot firing)</i>

23:47.024 --> 23:54.094
♪♪

23:54.096 --> 23:56.162
<i> (Gunshot firing)</i>

24:00.033 --> 24:02.601
<i> (Narrator) The streets are
turned into a battlefield,</i>

24:02.603 --> 24:07.105
<i> in what will come to be known
as "the Castellammarese war."</i>

24:12.544 --> 24:15.546
<i> (Selwyn Raab) The Castellammarese
war was the first time</i>

24:15.548 --> 24:21.051
<i> you had really a brutal war</i>
<i> between rival Italian gangs.</i>

24:21.053 --> 24:25.055
We had never hadthat before
in New York, or in America.

24:25.057 --> 24:27.624
<i> Nobody was safe</i>
<i> on the streets.</i>

24:27.626 --> 24:30.627
You had a situation
of what they call

24:30.629 --> 24:32.028
"going to the mattresses,"

24:32.030 --> 24:34.597
where they had to
hole up in safe places

24:34.599 --> 24:36.131
because you never knew.

24:36.133 --> 24:37.432
<i> If you went</i>
<i> out on the street,</i>

24:37.434 --> 24:38.666
<i> you could be</i>
<i> mowed down.</i>

24:38.668 --> 24:45.472
♪♪

24:45.474 --> 24:46.621
<i>(Meyer Lansky) This
is how he's doin' it</i>

24:46.646 --> 24:47.740
<i>down there. He's gonna
let us in on it.</i>

24:47.742 --> 24:49.475
How many stores got booze
in 'em right now?

24:49.477 --> 24:51.610
Uh, we've got about four
warehouses downtown.

24:51.612 --> 24:53.578
The next step, Charlie,

24:53.580 --> 24:55.713
I gotta connect with
(Indistinct), okay?

24:55.715 --> 24:57.548
We're gonna legally--
what about gere?

24:57.550 --> 24:59.082
No, we're gonna be able
to legally import scotch.

24:59.084 --> 25:00.910
<i>You understand me, Charlie?
What about here?</i>

25:00.935 --> 25:02.452
<i>I'm asking you, how
many stores here?</i>

25:02.454 --> 25:03.453
Hey! Hey!

25:03.455 --> 25:06.088
<i> (Indistinct shouting)</i>

25:06.090 --> 25:10.692
♪♪

25:10.694 --> 25:12.660
Get in!

25:12.662 --> 25:15.229
Go! Go! Go!

25:15.231 --> 25:17.130
Damn it!

25:19.066 --> 25:20.132
Shit!

25:26.706 --> 25:28.873
<i> (Grunting)</i>

25:31.643 --> 25:34.144
<i> (Narrator) As a mob war rages
on the streets of New York...</i>

25:34.146 --> 25:35.812
<i> (Grunting)</i>

25:35.814 --> 25:38.247
<i> ... one of Joe Masseria's</i>
<i> top lieutenants,</i>

25:38.249 --> 25:39.815
<i> Charles Luciano,</i>

25:39.817 --> 25:42.150
<i> is in the hands of</i>
<i> ruthless sicilian boss,</i>

25:42.152 --> 25:43.784
<i> Salvatore Maranzano.</i>

25:43.786 --> 25:47.687
<i> (Groaning, coughing)</i>
<i> Julius Caesar once said,</i>

25:47.689 --> 25:53.091
"it's easier to find men
who are willing to die...

25:53.093 --> 25:54.892
"Than to find those
who are willing

25:54.894 --> 26:00.763
"to endure pain
with Patience.

26:00.765 --> 26:03.532
<i> (Narrator) Salvatore Maranzano
is determined to send a message</i>

26:03.534 --> 26:07.702
<i> to Joe Masseria</i>
<i> and his crew.</i>

26:07.704 --> 26:09.637
<i> And for the next</i>
<i> eight hours,</i>

26:09.639 --> 26:12.172
<i> Luciano is beaten</i>
<i> and tortured.</i>

26:12.174 --> 26:19.245
♪♪

26:29.889 --> 26:32.123
Let's go.

26:32.125 --> 26:36.227
<i> (Narrator) Luciano was taken to
a remote area in Staten Island,</i>

26:36.229 --> 26:38.562
<i> where he's dumped</i>
<i> and left for dead.</i>

26:38.564 --> 26:45.635
♪♪

26:55.645 --> 26:57.846
<i> (Coughs)</i>

27:00.282 --> 27:03.850
<i> (Narrator) Against all odds,
Luciano somehow survives.</i>

27:07.588 --> 27:10.690
What's the word
on the street?

27:10.692 --> 27:12.825
It's not good.

27:18.231 --> 27:20.632
<i> (Narrator) Luciano's unlikely
recovery earns him a nickname</i>

27:20.634 --> 27:23.935
<i> that will last a</i>
<i> lifetime.</i>

27:23.937 --> 27:27.838
<i> "Lucky" Luciano.</i>

27:27.840 --> 27:29.973
<i> (Rich Cohen) I mean, he really
was stabbed and left for dead.</i>

27:29.975 --> 27:32.775
People don't take his
nickname seriously enough.

27:32.777 --> 27:34.777
The guy was lucky.

27:36.780 --> 27:39.648
Somebody's gonna
pay for this, Charlie.

27:39.650 --> 27:40.748
We're ready, Charlie.

27:40.750 --> 27:43.818
don't do anything yet.
You understand?

27:43.820 --> 27:47.822
'Cause they'll
be ready for us.

27:47.824 --> 27:51.292
<i> (Selwyn Raab) Luciano saw that
Maranzano was not gonna give in.</i>

27:51.294 --> 27:53.861
And he decided that
he was not only the equal,

27:53.863 --> 27:57.331
but he was the better of
Joe "the boss" Masseria.

27:57.333 --> 27:58.999
<i> This was an all-out war.</i>

27:59.001 --> 28:00.700
<i> And there wasn't gonna</i>
<i> be a peace treaty</i>

28:00.702 --> 28:03.302
<i> between these guys because</i>
<i> they hated each other.</i>

28:03.304 --> 28:08.839
And Luciano decided that
Masseria had to be removed.

28:10.708 --> 28:14.777
<i> (Narrator) The time has finally
come to kill Joe Masseria.</i>

28:14.779 --> 28:19.281
<i> And Luciano sees potential</i>
<i> in forging an alliance</i>

28:19.283 --> 28:20.915
<i> with the man</i>
<i> who just beat him</i>

28:20.917 --> 28:23.350
<i> to within an inch</i>
<i> of his life.</i>

28:29.824 --> 28:36.896
♪♪

28:37.831 --> 28:40.899
<i> (Indistinct)</i>

29:08.727 --> 29:11.862
You look better than
the last time I saw you.

29:11.864 --> 29:15.732
<i> (Sighs)</i>

29:18.435 --> 29:20.736
Why are you here?

29:20.738 --> 29:25.874
Because I respect you,
and I wanna work for you.

29:25.876 --> 29:27.375
I find it
hard to believe

29:27.377 --> 29:29.977
that the man who
killed for Masseria

29:29.979 --> 29:33.847
suddenly wants
to work for me.

29:33.849 --> 29:38.350
How does a traitor
have any honor?

29:38.352 --> 29:41.853
Let me prove it to you.

29:41.855 --> 29:44.088
How?

29:44.090 --> 29:46.090
I'll kill
Joe Masseria myself.

29:46.092 --> 29:53.163
♪♪

30:00.070 --> 30:03.906
To show you
my appreciation,

30:03.908 --> 30:08.310
you'll get a cut of
Masseria's rackets.

30:08.312 --> 30:10.445
I don't want a cut of
Masseria's rackets.

30:10.447 --> 30:12.280
I want 'em all.

30:12.282 --> 30:16.984
One more thing...
No more boss of bosses.

30:16.986 --> 30:19.319
<i> (Chuckles)</i>

30:19.321 --> 30:22.055
All right.

30:22.057 --> 30:24.791
<i> (Selwyn Raab) Lucky makes
a deal with Maranzano.</i>

30:24.793 --> 30:29.328
Lucky said,
"I'll take care of Masseria,

30:29.330 --> 30:32.064
"and the deal is that
this will end the war,

30:32.066 --> 30:33.965
"and there will be
just two of us,

30:33.967 --> 30:36.834
"and business
will flourish again."

30:36.836 --> 30:38.936
What did, uh,
Maranzano have to lose?

30:38.938 --> 30:42.372
So, he said,
"sure, go ahead."

30:42.374 --> 30:45.375
<i> (Narrator) Luciano has
the deal he came for.</i>

30:45.377 --> 30:47.477
<i> If he eliminates</i>
<i> Joe the boss,</i>

30:47.479 --> 30:52.249
<i> he will be one step closer</i>
<i> to ending the war,</i>

30:52.251 --> 30:55.085
<i> and seizing his own power</i>
<i> in the underworld.</i>

30:58.989 --> 31:06.061
♪♪

31:14.135 --> 31:16.970
<i> Tomorrow, I want you</i>
<i> to call up Masseria,</i>

31:16.972 --> 31:20.239
and you set up a meeting
in coney island.

31:20.241 --> 31:24.576
<i> (Narrator) Determined to put an
end to the Castellammarese war,</i>

31:24.578 --> 31:28.079
<i> Lucky Luciano and his gang</i>
<i> formulate a plan</i>

31:28.081 --> 31:32.216
<i> to kill mob boss,</i>
<i> Joe Masseria.</i>

31:32.218 --> 31:35.552
<i> But, first, they have</i>
<i> to get close to him.</i>

31:37.254 --> 31:41.257
<i> Though Masseria is</i>
<i> surrounded by bodyguards,</i>

31:41.259 --> 31:44.226
<i> Luciano knows that their
loyalty can be bought...</i>

31:49.064 --> 31:51.097
<i> ...for the right price.</i>

31:54.568 --> 31:56.669
<i> (sonny grosso) That's the
part of the chess game.</i>

31:56.671 --> 32:01.940
The loyalty that they profess
to have is bullshit.

32:01.942 --> 32:05.109
<i> They're as loyal</i>
<i> as they have to be.</i>

32:05.111 --> 32:06.243
And whatever they
can get away with,

32:06.245 --> 32:08.111
they try to
get away with.

32:21.291 --> 32:24.626
<i> Lucky, he knew, uh,</i>
<i> what a gargantuan appetite</i>

32:24.628 --> 32:29.196
Masseria had. He invited him to his
favorite restaurant in Brooklyn.

32:31.599 --> 32:33.666
Would you excuse me
for a second?

32:41.541 --> 32:43.542
<i> While they were</i>
<i> having dessert,</i>

32:43.544 --> 32:46.177
Lucky had said he had
to go to the bathroom,

32:46.179 --> 32:49.046
<i> and he left Masseria</i>
<i> alone at his table.</i>

32:50.948 --> 32:58.020
♪♪

33:08.096 --> 33:10.397
<i> (Gunshots firing)</i>

33:12.166 --> 33:19.238
♪♪

33:26.712 --> 33:29.346
<i> (Narrator) The man who ruled the
New York underworld for ten years,</i>

33:29.348 --> 33:35.385
<i> Joe "the boss" Masseria,</i>
<i> is dead.</i>

33:35.387 --> 33:40.757
<i> Luciano's biggest gamble yet</i>
<i> has just paid off.</i>

33:40.759 --> 33:45.128
<i> And while he stands to inherit
Masseria's criminal empire,</i>

33:45.130 --> 33:49.665
<i> he still has to answer to</i>
<i> the man who struck the deal.</i>

33:49.667 --> 33:53.468
<i> (Thunder rumbling)</i>

33:56.672 --> 33:59.140
Thank you for coming,
gentlemen.

33:59.142 --> 34:01.041
<i> (Narrator)</i>
<i> In may of 1931,</i>

34:01.043 --> 34:03.309
<i> Salvatore Maranzano</i>
<i> calls a meeting</i>

34:03.311 --> 34:06.712
<i> of the most powerful</i>
<i> gangsters in New York.</i>

34:06.714 --> 34:11.416
<i> Men like Joe bonanno,</i>
<i> Joe profaci,</i>

34:11.418 --> 34:16.220
<i> and Lucky Luciano,</i>
<i> to declare a victory.</i>

34:16.222 --> 34:18.655
<i> (Salvatore Maranzano)</i>
<i> The war, it's over now.</i>

34:18.657 --> 34:21.090
Masseria's dead.

34:21.092 --> 34:25.394
Starting today, we are gonna
leave all that behind us.

34:25.396 --> 34:30.132
We will do things
differently from now on.

34:30.134 --> 34:34.169
I think it's a good idea
for all of the bosses

34:34.171 --> 34:37.238
